      <header class="cod-title-block">
        <p class="cod-chapter-label">Chapter Four · Christian or Demonic?</p>
        <h1 class="cod-title">Translations</h1>
        <p class="cod-subtitle">You Haven't Been Reading the Word</p>
        <p class="cod-tagline">Every English Bible you have ever held comes with fingerprints. They are not always easy to see. But once you have seen them, you cannot unsee them.</p>
      </header>

      <p class="cod-pullquote">You have not been reading Scripture. You have been reading an edition.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Introduction</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Question No One Is Asking</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">There is a sentence every believer has said and every believer has heard. <em>"My Bible says..."</em> It sounds innocent. It sounds devout. It sounds like the sentence of a person submitted to the Word of Yahuah. But buried inside that short phrase is an assumption so large that almost no one stops to question it.</p>
      <p class="cod-body"><strong>Which Bible?</strong> Translated by whom? From which manuscripts? Under whose theological pressure? Passing through how many centuries of editing, vowel-adding, word-inserting, and name-erasing before landing on the tissue-thin page in your lap?</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The believer assumes his Bible hands him the Word the way the Word was originally given — whole, clean, unchanged. That assumption is almost entirely false. Every translation is a decision. Every decision has a maker. Every maker had a theology. And the English Bible most believers are reading was shaped, in some of its most critical verses, by men who had already absorbed the very doctrines scripture was supposed to correct.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">This chapter is going to walk you through the fingerprints. Not to shake your faith in the Scriptures — but to restore it to the <em>right</em> thing. The Word of Yahuah is inspired. The editors, copyists, and translators were not.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part One</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Myth of Direct Transmission</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">Most believers picture the Bible arriving in their hands through something like a straight line. Yahuah inspired the authors. The authors wrote. The text was preserved. The text was translated. The believer reads the result. Simple, linear, faithful.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Reality is nothing like that. The path from the original Hebrew and Greek manuscripts to your English Bible passes through Aramaic Targums, the Septuagint, the Masoretic editors of Tiberias, the Latin Vulgate of Jerome, a thousand years of Catholic monastic copying, the frantic printing of Erasmus, the political theater of the Reformation, the committees of King James, and the dozens of competing modern translations that followed. <strong>Each of those steps left fingerprints.</strong> Each one bent the text — sometimes innocently, sometimes not.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The Hebrew of the Old Testament was originally written without vowels. That is not a defect — Hebrew is designed that way. The reader supplies the vowels from knowledge of the spoken language. But it means that when a Hebrew manuscript sat silently in a scroll for a thousand years, the men who later decided <em>which</em> vowels belonged on each word were in a position of extraordinary power. They could bend the meaning of an entire passage by the placement of a single dot.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The Greek of the New Testament was written in what is called <em>scriptio continua</em> — all capitals, no spaces between words, no punctuation. Again, not a defect. But the men who later decided where one word ended and the next began, where a sentence broke, where a paragraph divided — those men had theological preferences. And those preferences ran downhill into your translation.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Then there was the matter of which manuscripts to even work from. There are thousands of ancient biblical manuscripts. They do not all agree. They disagree on thousands of small details and several large ones. When a translator selects which manuscript family to follow, he is making a doctrinal decision, not a technical one. <strong>Every English Bible you have ever read is the product of thousands of these decisions.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">With that in view, the journey from the breath of Yahuah to the page in your hand starts to look less like a straight line and more like a long hallway of doors. Each door was opened by a man. Each man made a choice. Most of those choices were fine. Some of them rewrote doctrine. A few of them changed who your Messiah is.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Two</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Masoretic Deception</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">The Old Testament your pastor preaches from is almost certainly translated from a source called the <strong>Masoretic Text</strong>. The name sounds ancient and authoritative. Most believers assume it is the Hebrew Bible that has existed unchanged since the days of the prophets. It is not.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The Masoretic Text was produced between the sixth and tenth centuries AD — that is, between five hundred and nine hundred years <em>after</em> the resurrection of the Messiah — by a school of Hebrew scribes known as the Masoretes, operating primarily out of Tiberias under the leadership of the ben Asher family. These men were not descendants of the Temple priesthood. They were not the heirs of the apostles. <strong>They were Jewish rabbis who had firmly rejected Yahushua as Messiah</strong> and were preserving the Hebrew Scriptures within a religion defined, in part, <em>against</em> Him.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Their most significant contribution was the introduction of vowel points — small dots and dashes added above and below the Hebrew consonants to fix the pronunciation of every word in the text. Before their work, the Hebrew Bible was a sea of consonants. After their work, every word had a locked-in pronunciation. A system invented a thousand years after the last prophet spoke now decided how every ambiguous word would be read forever.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Most of the time this was harmless. Sometimes it was not. When a word could legitimately be read two different ways depending on the vowels — when one reading pointed toward the Messiah and the other reading away from Him — the Masoretes made a choice. They were not neutral. They were theologically committed opponents of the one that text was written to describe.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">One well-known example is the handling of Psalm 22 — the psalm the Messiah Himself quoted from the stake. In verse 16, the Hebrew consonants can read either <em>"they pierced my hands and feet"</em> or, with a single vowel shift, <em>"like a lion my hands and feet."</em> The older Dead Sea Scrolls read <em>"pierced."</em> The Masoretic text reads <em>"like a lion."</em> The vowel decision the Masoretes made in the tenth century pulls the psalm away from a crucified Messiah. One dot. That is how easy it is to bend Scripture when you get to place the vowels a thousand years after the fact.</p>

      <details class="cod-deepdive">
        <summary>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-label">
            <span class="cod-deepdive-icon">✦</span>
            <span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-title">Go Deeper — The Fingerprints: Words That Got Bent</span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-hint">Easter in Acts 12, church for ekklesia, hell collapses four words</span>
            </span>
          </span>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-chevron">▾</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="cod-deepdive-body">

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">"Easter" in Acts 12:4</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">The King James Bible contains one of the most blatant pagan insertions in any English translation. Acts 12:4 reads that Herod intended to kill Peter <em>"after Easter."</em> The Greek word in the manuscript is <em>pascha</em> — the Passover. Every other occurrence of <em>pascha</em> in the New Testament is correctly translated <em>Passover</em>. In Acts 12:4 alone, the translators replaced the Hebraic feast with the name of a pagan fertility goddess. Modern translations mostly corrected this — but the KJV carried it for four hundred years, and millions of believers still argue Easter has biblical sanction because of one verse that was mistranslated on purpose.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">"Church" for Ekklesia</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">The Greek word in every New Testament reference is <em>ekklesia</em> — meaning a called-out assembly. It is a civic word, not a religious one. When believers in the first century said <em>ekklesia</em>, they meant the body of people who had been called out of the world system into covenant with Yahuah. They did not mean a building. They did not mean an institution. They did not mean a denomination.</p>
          <p class="cod-body">But when William Tyndale first translated the New Testament into English in the 1520s, he used the word <em>congregation</em> — accurately capturing the sense of <em>ekklesia</em>. King James's translators deliberately overruled him. They were instructed to use <em>church</em>. The English word <em>church</em> derives from <em>kyriakon</em> — "belonging to the lord" — a word that functioned in the pagan world before it ever attached itself to Christian use, and which slotted perfectly into the institutional language Rome needed to maintain its grip on English-speaking believers. <strong>Every time a believer says "I'm going to church," he is using a word scripture does not.</strong></p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">"Hell" — Four Different Words Collapsed into One</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">The English word <em>hell</em> in the KJV does the work of four distinct original-language words that mean different things:</p>
          <p class="cod-body"><strong>Sheol</strong> (Hebrew) — the grave, the pit of the dead. Appears 65 times in the Old Testament. Translated "hell," "grave," and "pit" inconsistently, with doctrinal results that have confused readers for centuries.</p>
          <p class="cod-body"><strong>Hades</strong> (Greek) — the Greek equivalent of sheol. The place of the dead, not a place of conscious torment.</p>
          <p class="cod-body"><strong>Gehenna</strong> (Greek) — a literal valley outside Jerusalem (the Valley of Hinnom) where refuse was burned. Yahushua used it as an image of final judgment.</p>
          <p class="cod-body"><strong>Tartaroo</strong> (Greek) — appears once, in 2 Peter 2:4, describing the holding place for the rebellious heavenly beings.</p>
          <p class="cod-body">The translators collapsed all four into a single English word. The result is a "hell" doctrine stitched together from four different source-words that meant different things — and then read back into the text as if it had always been one unified concept.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">"Grace" Divorced from Covenant</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">The Hebrew word <em>chen</em> and the Greek word <em>charis</em> both carry the sense of unearned favor shown within a covenant relationship. Grace in Scripture is always <em>toward</em> a people defined by the covenant, not a release <em>from</em> the covenant. Modern translations and, especially, modern sermons have used the word <em>grace</em> in ways that erase the Torah as the framework within which grace operates. The word itself has been hijacked to carry theology the Hebrew never contained. A believer hearing "we're under grace, not law" from his pulpit is hearing English with four hundred years of Reformation baggage pasted onto a word that originally meant something very different.</p>

        </div>
      </details>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Three</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Latin Vulgate and the Inserted Trinity</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">If the Masoretic Text is the shadow over the Old Testament, the <strong>Latin Vulgate</strong> is the shadow over the New. Between AD 382 and 405, a man named Jerome produced a Latin translation of the Bible under a commission from Pope Damasus I — the same imperial church system that produced the canon lists of Hippo and Carthage. For the next thousand years, the Vulgate <em>was</em> the Bible in the West. Priests read it. Monks copied it. Councils quoted it. When the Reformers finally broke out into vernacular translation, they were pushing back against a book that had already held Christianity in a Latin-shaped mold for a millennium.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Most of the Vulgate is a reasonable translation. But a small number of its verses were either flatly invented or heavily bent to support doctrines the original manuscripts do not support. The most notorious example is 1 John 5:7 — the single most explicit "Trinity verse" in your Bible. In the King James Version, it reads:</p>

      <div class="cod-verse-compare">
        <div class="cod-verse-row cod-verse-strike">
          <p class="cod-verse-label">1 John 5:7 — KJV (as printed)</p>
          <p class="cod-verse-text">"For there are three that bear record in heaven, the Father, the Word, and the Holy Ghost: and these three are one."</p>
        </div>
        <div class="cod-verse-row">
          <p class="cod-verse-label">What the earliest Greek manuscripts actually say</p>
          <p class="cod-verse-text">[The entire phrase is absent. Verse 7 simply reads: "For there are three that bear witness — the Spirit, and the water, and the blood; and these three agree as one."]</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="cod-body">The bolded phrase about "the Father, the Word, and the Holy Ghost" — known as the <strong>Johannine Comma</strong> — does not appear in any Greek manuscript of 1 John before the fourteenth century. Not one. It appears for the first time as a marginal note in a Latin manuscript of the Vulgate in the fourth or fifth century, slipped into the body of the text by a copyist at some point after that, and then carried forward by Rome for a thousand years. Erasmus, compiling the first printed Greek New Testament in the sixteenth century, originally left it out — because it was not in any Greek manuscript he had. Under pressure from the Catholic establishment, he reluctantly included it in his third edition. And that third edition is the source text behind the Textus Receptus, which is the source text behind the King James, which is the source text behind the doctrine that sits in most evangelical pews today.</p>
      <p class="cod-body"><strong>The clearest proof-text for the Trinity in the English Bible is an insertion.</strong> Not a translation. Not a rendering. An insertion — a phrase added to the text centuries after the apostle died, by scribes serving a theological system the apostle never taught.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">When the modern church builds a central doctrine on a verse the apostle did not write, and then fights anyone who points that out, you are looking at the exact pattern the rest of this series has been exposing. The doctrine came first. The verse was produced to support it.</p>

      <details class="cod-deepdive">
        <summary>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-label">
            <span class="cod-deepdive-icon">✦</span>
            <span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-title">Go Deeper — Erasmus, the Textus Receptus, and the Rushed King James</span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-hint">How a hurried sixteenth-century printing job became "the original Bible"</span>
            </span>
          </span>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-chevron">▾</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="cod-deepdive-body">

          <p class="cod-body">In 1516, a Dutch scholar named Desiderius Erasmus produced the first printed Greek New Testament. He was in a race with a Spanish project that had beaten him to the manuscript-collecting but not to the press. Erasmus worked so quickly that his first edition is widely considered one of the most poorly edited books of its era. He had access to fewer than a dozen late Greek manuscripts, most of them from the twelfth century or later — not originals, not early copies, but medieval handwritten volumes sitting in monastery libraries.</p>

          <p class="cod-body">For several passages of Revelation, Erasmus did not have <em>any</em> Greek manuscript. He filled in the gaps by back-translating from the Latin Vulgate into his own Greek. That back-translated Greek — Erasmus's best guess at what the Greek <em>might</em> have said — ended up in his printed edition. From there, it passed into every subsequent revision of what became known as the <strong>Textus Receptus</strong> — the "Received Text" — which became the standard Greek New Testament of Protestantism for the next three centuries.</p>

          <p class="cod-body">The Textus Receptus is the text underneath every major English Bible from Tyndale through the Geneva Bible and into the 1611 King James Version. When the KJV translators sat down to work, they were not translating from pristine apostolic Greek. They were translating from Erasmus's rushed edition, heavily stitched together, corrected by him and others under commercial and political pressure, and in several passages literally retro-translated from Latin into Greek and then into English.</p>

          <p class="cod-body">This does not mean the KJV is garbage. It does mean it is not the untouchable article many believers have been taught it is. <strong>Every "King James only" argument collapses under the simple question: which edition?</strong> The 1611? The 1769 Oxford revision most modern KJVs actually follow? The Cambridge? The paragraphed editions? The editions with and without the apocrypha? The editions that corrected Erasmus's back-translated verses in Revelation? The sacred status the KJV enjoys in certain circles has no foundation in history. It is a twentieth-century American construction.</p>

          <p class="cod-body">The modern English translations that rely on older, more numerous, and more geographically diverse manuscripts (the Nestle-Aland or Critical Text) are generally closer to what the apostles actually wrote in disputed passages. But they too have editorial preferences, committee politics, and doctrinal pressure. <em>No</em> English translation escapes the hallway of doors. The answer is not to find the magic translation. The answer is to know enough to see the fingerprints on whatever translation you have.</p>

        </div>
      </details>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Four</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Missing Name</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">If there is one fingerprint that exposes everything else, it is this one. Open almost any English Bible, turn to the Old Testament, and scan for the word <strong>LORD</strong> — printed in small capital letters. You will see it everywhere. In the King James, it appears <strong>6,828 times</strong>. And in almost every one of those occurrences, the underlying Hebrew is not the word for "lord" at all. It is the four letters of the sacred name:</p>

      <div class="cod-hebrew">
        <p class="cod-hebrew-word">יהוה</p>
        <p class="cod-hebrew-translit">YHWH</p>
        <p class="cod-hebrew-meaning">the covenant name of the Creator</p>
      </div>

      <p class="cod-body">The translators did not render the name. They erased it. Nearly seven thousand times, the personal covenant name of the Creator was removed from the text of the Old Testament and replaced with a title. <em>LORD</em>. A generic honorific that any king, any master, any slave owner could wear. The name Yahuah gave Mosheh at the burning bush — the name He said would be <em>His memorial unto all generations</em> (Exodus 3:15) — was crossed out seven thousand times.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">This was not an accident. The decision traces back to a superstition that entered Judaism in the centuries before the Messiah, in which the divine name was considered too holy to pronounce. The Masoretes, when they added their vowel points, deliberately inserted the vowels of the Hebrew word <em>Adonai</em> ("lord") underneath the consonants YHWH — a signal to the reader <em>not</em> to read the name but to substitute the title. When the Septuagint translators rendered the Old Testament into Greek, they continued the substitution with <em>Kyrios</em>. Jerome, rendering the Vulgate, used <em>Dominus</em>. By the time the text reached English, the name had been buried under three layers of replacement titles.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The result: most believers go their entire lives without ever pronouncing the name of the One they claim to worship. They pray to <em>the Lord</em>. They sing about <em>the Lord</em>. They read about <em>the Lord</em>. But Yahuah said it is by <em>His name</em> He is to be known. Not by a title. Not by a euphemism. By the name.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">And in the New Testament, the same pattern shows up in miniature. The Messiah was born into a Hebrew-speaking family. His name, given by the messenger to Miryam (Mary), was <strong>Yahushua</strong> — a Hebrew name meaning "Yah is salvation." The Greek rendering of that name is <em>Iesous</em>. The Latin is <em>Iesus</em>. Early English manuscripts rendered it as <em>Iesus</em> or <em>Iesu</em>. The letter <em>J</em> did not exist in English until the sixteenth century, and the name "Jesus" as it is pronounced today — with a hard J and the "zuss" ending — did not take shape until the seventeenth century. <strong>The name "Jesus" is younger than the King James Bible.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">This is not a minor point of piety. It is the fingerprint of an entire project. The One whose name means <em>Yahuah saves</em> had that linguistic testimony erased from His own title. The Father's name has been buried seven thousand times under <em>LORD</em>. The Son's name has been reshaped by four centuries of Latinization and Anglicization until it no longer carries the sound of the Father's name within it. <em>Yah-ushua</em> — Yah saves — became <em>Jesus</em>. The testimony was edited out.</p>

      <p class="cod-pullquote">If you cannot find His name, you cannot call on His name. And the translators made sure you could not find it.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Five</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">So What Now?</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">None of this means you throw your Bible away. The Word of Yahuah is still in there. The Hebrew behind your Old Testament is still His word. The Greek behind your New Testament is still the witness of the apostles. The translators did not destroy the text — they filtered it. Your job is to learn what the filter changed, and to read through it instead of being trapped behind it.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">A handful of practical habits make most of the fingerprints visible. <strong>Look up the original words.</strong> A Strong's Concordance and an online interlinear are now free and instant. Any word that carries theological weight in your Bible deserves to be checked against its Hebrew or Greek root. <strong>Compare translations.</strong> Not to find the "right" one — no such translation exists — but to see where the translators disagreed with each other, because those are the seams where the decisions were made. <strong>Restore the names.</strong> Every time your Bible says <em>the LORD</em>, read <em>Yahuah</em>. Every time it says <em>Jesus</em>, know that the name He was given by the messenger was <em>Yahushua</em>. Let the Hebrew speak underneath the English.</p>
      <p class="cod-body"><strong>And always measure the New against the Old.</strong> The Torah, the Prophets, and the Writings were the only Scriptures Yahushua and the apostles ever referred to as Scripture. They are the foundation. The New Testament is the witness of those who walked with the Messiah, but the witness has passed through the editors' hands far more times than the foundation has. When the two appear to conflict — almost always, the conflict is a translator's fingerprint, not the apostle's.</p>

      <div class="cod-divider">◆</div>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Six</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Verdict</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-pullquote">Christian or demonic?</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The Word of Yahuah, as He originally spoke it, is set-apart, perfect, and sufficient. It is the foundation of everything. But <strong>the English Bible in your lap is not the Word itself — it is a translation of a translation of a translation, filtered through centuries of editing, vowel-adding, word-inserting, and name-erasing by men who were not neutral.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">The Masoretes added vowels that bent entire psalms away from the Messiah. The Vulgate carried an inserted Trinity verse that no apostle ever wrote. Erasmus rushed a Greek text and back-translated from Latin where his manuscripts ran out. The KJV committee chose <em>church</em> where Tyndale chose <em>congregation</em>, chose <em>Easter</em> where every other verse said <em>Passover</em>, and erased the divine name nearly seven thousand times in favor of a generic title. Every one of those choices shaped the Christianity most believers now assume is simply "what the Bible says."</p>
      <p class="cod-body">This is not a reason to despair. It is a reason to wake up. <strong>The Word is still there.</strong> Under the fingerprints, underneath the vowel points, beneath the Latin and the English and the committee edits, the breath of Yahuah still carries. But you will not hear it clearly if you assume the translation is the text. You will hear it when you learn to read past the editors and listen to the Hebrew underneath.</p>
      <p class="cod-pullquote">Stop saying "my Bible says." Start asking what the Hebrew says. That is the difference between reading Scripture — and reading an edition of Scripture someone else produced for you.</p>

      <div class="cod-end"><span class="cod-end-mark">◆</span></div>
    </div>
